      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANMicroplastics have been found in the digestive tracts of every marine mammal surveyed in a new study of animals washed up on Britain's beaches, according to scientists. According to the BBC, scientists from the University of Exeter and Plymouth Marine Laboratory, or PML, looked at 50 animals, including 10 species of dolphins, seals and whales. According to the Guardian, researchers found that nylon made up more than 60 percent of the microplastics, coming from possible sources like fishing rope and nets, clothing microfibers and toothbrush bristles. Polyethylene terephthalate, or PET, was also widely present in the marine animals studied. According to the scientists, on average, 5.5 plastic particles were discovered in the guts of each animal. According to the BBC, 84 percent of the microplastics found were synthetic fibers, while the remaining was fragments of food packaging and plastic bottles. The results were published in the journal Scientific Reports. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Microplastics discovered in surveyed all marine animals2. Nylon from fishing rope, nets, clothing and toothbrushes made up more than 60 percent of microplastics3. PET plastic was also found in marine animals surveyed4. Majority of microplastics came from synthetic fibers, food packaging and plastic bottlesVOICEOVER (in English): "According to the BBC, scientists from the University of Exeter and Plymouth Marine Laboratory looked at 50 animals, including 10 species of dolphins, seals and whales and found microplastics in all the animals surveyed." "According to the Guardian, researchers found that nylon made up more than 60 percent of the microplastics, coming from possible sources like fishin