      <title>Rising temperatures could change the ocean's color, study finds</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe oceans are expected to become bluer and greener by the end of the end of this century, according to a study published in Nature Communications.Researchers from MIT and the University of Southampton noted that phytoplankton at the surface of the sea absorbs and reflects the sunlight. This gives the ocean its current bluish-green hue.Rising temperatures and acidity will cause phytoplankton in the water to decrease in number, essentially changing the color of the ocean as less sunlight is absorbed.The study explains that parts of the ocean will gradually turn a deep blue in color while others gradually turn darker green over the next 80 years.However, this change probably won't be visible to the naked eye, lead author of the study, Dr. Stephanie Dutkiewicz, told the BBC.The researchers were experimenting on the assumption that ocean temperatures would have risen by 3 degrees Celsius by 2100.Weather patterns such as El Nino or La Nina could also change the color of the ocean, according to a press release by MIT.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The ocean turning a dark shade of blue and green2. Phytoplankton and sun rays bouncing off the water3. Phytoplankton decreasing in number, causing the color of the ocean to change4. Part of the ocean turning deep blue while another part of the ocean turns deep green in colorVOICEOVER (in English): "According to a study in published in Nature Communications, the oceans are expected to become bluer and greener by the end of the 21st Century.""Researchers from MIT and the University of Southampton noted that phytoplankton at the surface of the sea absorbs and reflects the sunlight. "This gives the ocean its current bluish-green hue." "Howeve