      <title>China testing out 'gait-recognition' technology</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANChinese authorities are testing a new system that analyzes people's gait when they walk.  According to the South China Morning Post, Chinese police are testing a new technology called 'gait recognition' that analyzes live videos and stores data of how a person walks.The system was developed by Watrix, a Chinese artificial intelligence start-up. They claim the program can detect someone's walk from 50 meters away regardless of whether they are facing the camera.It does this by creating silhouettes of people in videos and studying their body contour, their arm movement while walking, whether they have a toe-in or a toe-out gait, among other elements. All these components allow them to identify each person's unique 'walking style.' Authorities in the Chinese cities of Beijing, Shanghai, and Chongqing are among the cities that have already tried the product. The newest version of the program is able to analyze live camera feeds of megacities.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Woman is scanned as she is walking2. People walking on street are detected and scanned by Watrix3. Elements that Watrix analyzes from individual's walks4. Cities testing the programsVOICEOVER (in English): "According to the South China Morning Post, Chinese police are testing a new technology called 'gait recognition' that analyzes live videos and stores data of how a person walks.""The system was developed by Watrix, a Chinese artificial intelligence start-up." "They claim the program can detect someone's walk from 50 meters away regardless of whether they are facing the camera.""It does this by creating silhouettes of people in videos and studying their body contour, their arm movement while walking, whether they have a toe-in or a toe-out gait, among other elements." "All these components allow them to identify each person's unique 'walking style.'""Authorities in the Chinese cities of Beijing, Shanghai, and Chongqing are among the cities that have already tried the product." "The newest version of the program is able to analyze live camera feeds of megacities."SOURCES: South China Morning Posthttps://www.scmp.com/tech/start-ups/article/2187600/chinese-police-surveillance-gets-boost-ai-start-watrix-technology-can***]]></description>
