      <title>How the Democratic party will stage its primary debates</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe Democratic National Committee has announced that it has limited the number of presidential debate participants to 20 candidates. The debates will be held in June and July on two separate consecutive nights depending on the number of candidates that qualify.The Associated Press reports that candidates will qualify for the debate if they earn at least 1 percent support in three separate national or early primary state polls conducted from January 1 to two weeks before the debate.They can also qualify if they receive campaign donations from 65,000 people across 20 different states, with a minimum of 200 unique donors per state.Candidates will be assigned randomly to the two stages regardless of each candidates polling percentages.Efforts for a fairer and less poll-driven selection process for the nominees comes after voters in the 2016 elections felt the DNC was biased against the then outsider Senator Bernie Sanders.These claims stemmed mainly from allegations by former DNC chair Donna Brazile. In her book 'Hacks: The Inside Story of the Break-ins and Breakdowns that Put Donald Trump in the White House' Brazile accuses Hillary Clinton of rigging the primary elections in her favor by signing a joint fundraising agreement with the DNC and the Hillary Victory Fund.The exact dates and locations for the debates are yet to be confirmed, however, the DNC announced that NBC, MSNBC and Telemundo will broadcast the June debates on back-to-back nights, and CNN will broadcast the July debate on back-to-back nights. There will be a total of 12 debates. ________________RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Democratic National Committee limits first debates to 20 candidates2. Candidates qualify if they earn at least 1 percent support in national or early state polls 3. Candidates qualify depending on number of donations they receive4. Candidates are assigned randomly to one of two stagesVOICEOVER (in English): "The Democratic National Committee has announced that it has limited the number of presidential debate participants to 20 candidates." "The debates will be held in June and July on two separate consecutive nights depending on the number of candidates that qualify." "The Associated Press reports that candidates will qualify for the debate if they earn at least 1 percent support in three separate national or early primary state polls conducted from January 1 to two weeks before the debate.""They can also qualify if they receive campaign donations from 65,000 people across 20 different states, with a minimum of 200 unique donors per state.""Candidates will be assigned randomly to the two stages regardless of each candidates polling percentages."SOURCES: Associated Press, Politico, Voxhttps://www.apnews.com/03172a56519d4b9f8404bbb2e6be3742https://www.politico.com/story/2019/02/14/dnc-fundraising-polling-early-debates-1170182https://www.vox.com/2019/2/14/18225341/dnc-tom-perez-debates-2020-president***]]></description>
